7. crispo. Juv. iv, 81, Crispi jucunda senectus. He was famed as much for his eloquence as for his wealth, the latter amounting to 200,000,000 sesterces (or 300,000‚000‚ Tac. de Orat. c. 8). By his tact and power to make himself useful to a government, he exercised great influence in Vespasian’s reign, and at a later time retained the favor of Domitian. Juvenal l.c. describes his character, vv. 81—93.
